Any system that has Git, Node.js, TiddlyWiki, Node-Red, and a text editor installed can be the host of the system.

I use Raspberry Pis. The [[rpi-zero|http://wikis.poc2go.net/rpi-zero]] wiki has my notes on setting up a small [[Raspberry Pi Zero 2W|https://www.amazon.com/Raspberry-Zero-Bluetooth-RPi-2W/dp/B09LH5SBPS/ref=sr_1_1?adgrpid=1330410311104656&dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.3BENuF2Ktu1UHOlVshSOQR65x4OX3ptA7XWs1dRUN9b4YWnC1cxI8k4aAVib31h4SQ9AVxwbOINlsdxp5mO9BaDdEydKdAeQQ4twhnXN6CY9dLeboG3tD-L7OZfImolOvA_LkTZ3YIJ1AjuhVvSZw4X8JvmjVo8LLwn4sT3z04jiVDkBTVFmZZK4Nj49CKDgKGNv9RYIuKeluWWhbzTuiFxAKOHW6mPpY9itYR7MyT0.1Xt0rT8hTf21LWLYsuDLDQmPfu228AjQQcfFZDkzha8&dib_tag=se&hvadid=83150818185332&hvbmt=be&hvdev=c&hvlocphy=77230&hvnetw=o&hvqmt=e&hvtargid=kwd-83151458158215%3Aloc-190&hydadcr=726_1014950964&keywords=raspberry+pi+zero+2w&mcid=fd299bc2a4de3ccc91508449cdf00384&qid=1747765969&sr=8-1]] which can run the system.

* Not the fastest on the planet - but can carry in your pocket.
* Powered off any USB port
* Is only around $40 USD for the hardware (Pi, heatsink, cable, SD card reader)

For wikis that face the web, I use larger Pis - the RPI 4B+ is cheap and has plenty of power. My internet bandwidth however is not the greatest ;( - so is the limiting factor.


 